<h2>Results</h2>
<p>Surveying citizens between one and four years since they got their first transfers, we demonstrate that when feelings of their relative poverty are not made salient (due to being in the non-poverty primed group), citizens only minimally reward government for the programme in terms of higher political support (Figure 3, panel a). But, when feelings of relative poverty are salient (due to being in the poverty primed group), beneficiaries have significantly higher political support than do non-beneficiaries (Figure 3, panel b). </p>
